# Production compose interpolation contract (E14 T1). Copy to production.env and edit, then:
#
#   docker compose --env-file production.env \
#     -f deploy/compose/compose.yaml -f deploy/compose/production.yml up -d
#
# This is the hand-run production profile — there is NO `palai prod` command; the operator
# drives compose directly (docs/operations/install.md). Secrets are NEVER set here: they live
# as FILES under ${PALAI_HOME} and reach the stack through the top-level `secrets:` blocks.

# Absolute path to the data dir `palai init` created. Holds ca/ (CA + edge server cert),
# api-key (bootstrap key), runner-token, secrets/ (pg-password, provider-one, master-key).
PALAI_HOME=/absolute/path/to/.palai

# The ONLY host-published port: the TLS edge (maps to the edge container's :443). The
# control-plane API and the runner gateway are NOT published — they stay on the internal
# compose network, reachable only behind the edge.
PALAI_EDGE_PORT=443

# The reference engine image the runner launches per lease. Build/pin it as your deploy
# requires (release-digest pinning is E18); a hand-run production compose must set it.
PALAI_ENGINE_IMAGE=palai/reference-engine:local

# The compose project name — the runner labels every engine sandbox with it so teardown reaps
# exactly this stack's engines. Set it to the `-p` you bring the stack up under.
PALAI_COMPOSE_PROJECT=palai-prod

# Dispatch exec-path workers. Production defaults to 1 (a real create -> engine -> terminal
# round-trip); the base local profile defaults to 0 (queued-only).
PALAI_DISPATCH_WORKERS=1

# Model provider the exec-path routes to: "fake" (deterministic, no network/credential) or
# "provider-one" (live OpenAI; PALAI_MODEL sets the model id, credential is the provider-one
# file-secret). A real deployment typically sets a DB model route per project instead (E13 T8).
PALAI_MODEL_PROVIDER=fake
PALAI_MODEL=

# --- MANDATORY: the secret master key (NOT set here — this documents the FILE it points to) ---
#
# The production control-plane REFUSES to boot unless ${PALAI_HOME}/secrets/master-key holds a
# real 32-byte key (production-entrypoint.sh fails closed). Generate it ONCE:
#
#   openssl rand -hex 32 > ${PALAI_HOME}/secrets/master-key && chmod 600 ${PALAI_HOME}/secrets/master-key
#
# The guard rejects an unset file, an empty file, an all-zero key, and the literal placeholder
# "REPLACE_WITH_OPENSSL_RAND_HEX_32". The bootstrap key (${PALAI_HOME}/api-key, minted by
# `palai init`) is likewise rejected if left as "REPLACE_WITH_A_REAL_BOOTSTRAP_KEY".
